# Francis Fane (politician)

**Francis Fane** [KC](/King%27s_Counsel) (c. 1698 – 28 May 1757) was a prominent British [Member of Parliament](/Member_of_Parliament) and Commissioner for Trade and the Plantations during the early to mid-18th century. A figure of considerable legal and political influence, Fane navigated the complexities of Georgian-era governance with a sharp legal mind and a career marked by both parliamentary service and administrative roles. His life, though not widely celebrated in historical narratives, offers a compelling glimpse into the intersections of law, trade, and politics in 18th-century Britain.

## Early Life and Education

Francis Fane was born around 1698, the eldest son of [Henry Fane](/Henry_Fane_of_Brympton), a prosperous Bristol merchant whose commercial ventures laid the foundation for the family's ascent into the political and social echelons of the time. The Fane family, though not of ancient nobility, traced their lineage back to [Francis Fane, 1st Earl of Westmorland](/Francis_Fane,_1st_Earl_of_Westmorland), a connection that would later play a significant role in the fortunes of Francis's younger brother, [Thomas Fane](/Thomas_Fane,_8th_Earl_of_Westmorland).

Fane's education was befitting a man of his ambitions. He attended [King's College, Cambridge](/King%27s_College,_Cambridge), where he graduated in 1715. His academic pursuits were followed by legal training at the [Middle Temple](/Middle_Temple), one of the four [Inns of Court](/Inns_of_Court) in London. Called to the bar in 1721, Fane quickly established himself as a competent and astute legal mind, a reputation that would serve him well in his future political career.

Upon the death of his father in 1726, Fane inherited the family estate, a transition that marked the beginning of his independent career. The following year, 1727, was a pivotal one for Fane. He was appointed [King's Counsel](/King%27s_Counsel), a prestigious recognition of his legal acumen, and became a bencher at the Middle Temple, a position that granted him considerable influence within the legal profession. That same year, he secured a position as standing counsel to the [Board of Trade and Plantations](/Board_of_Trade), a role he would hold for over two decades until 1746. This appointment placed him at the heart of Britain's colonial administration, where he would have been involved in the oversight of trade policies, colonial governance, and the economic exploitation of Britain's overseas territories.

In 1731, Fane purchased the estate at [Brympton d'Evercy](/Brympton_d%27Evercy), near Yeovil in Somerset. The acquisition of this property was not merely a personal investment but a strategic move that bolstered his social standing and political influence in the region. Brympton d'Evercy, a manor house with a history dating back to the medieval period, became a symbol of Fane's growing stature. The estate would later pass to his younger brother, Thomas, who would go on to inherit the Earldom of Westmorland.

## Parliamentary Career

Fane's entry into Parliament marked the beginning of a political career that spanned nearly three decades. His first foray into the House of Commons came in 1727 when he was elected as the Member of Parliament for [Taunton](/Taunton_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), a constituency in Somerset. This parliament, which first convened for business on 27 January 1728 (N.S.), was part of the political landscape dominated by the Whig party under the leadership of [Robert Walpole](/Robert_Walpole), often regarded as Britain's first de facto Prime Minister. Fane's alignment with the Whigs, the party of trade and commercial interests, was a natural fit given his background as a merchant's son and his role in the Board of Trade.

Fane's representation of Taunton continued into the next parliament, which was summoned to meet on 13 June 1734. During this period, he also served as [Solicitor-General](/Solicitor_General_for_England_and_Wales) to [Queen Caroline](/Caroline_of_Ansbach), the wife of King George II. This appointment, which he held from 13 May 1729 until the Queen's death in 1737, further cemented his reputation as a trusted legal advisor within the royal court. His duties would have included providing legal counsel on matters pertaining to the Queen's interests, a role that required both discretion and legal expertise.

In 1739, Fane was appointed chairman of the ways and means committee, a position he held until 1751. This committee was responsible for overseeing the financial affairs of the nation, including taxation and public expenditure. His tenure in this role coincided with a period of significant financial challenges for Britain, including the aftermath of the [South Sea Bubble](/South_Sea_Company) and the ongoing costs of maintaining Britain's colonial empire. Fane's legal background would have been invaluable in navigating these complexities.

Fane's parliamentary career took him beyond Taunton. In 1741, he was elected as the Member of Parliament for [Petersfield](/Petersfield_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), a constituency in Hampshire. This parliament, summoned to meet on 25 June 1741, was marked by increasing political tensions, including the fall of Walpole's government in 1742. Fane's ability to retain his seat during this period of political upheaval is a testament to his political acumen and the respect he commanded among his peers.

In 1746, Fane's long-standing association with the Board of Trade and Plantations was formalized when he was appointed as one of its commissioners. This role placed him at the center of Britain's colonial administration, where he would have been involved in shaping policies that governed the [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) in North America, as well as other British territories in the Caribbean and beyond. That same year, he was re-elected to Parliament, this time representing [Ilchester](/Ilchester_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), another Somerset constituency. This parliament, which first sat on 12 November 1747, was dominated by the [Pelham](/Henry_Pelham) ministry, which continued many of the policies initiated under Walpole.

Fane's later years in Parliament saw him representing [Lyme Regis](/Lyme_Regis_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), a coastal town in Dorset. He held this seat from 1754 until his death in 1757. His final years in Parliament were marked by the growing tensions that would eventually lead to the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War), a conflict that would reshape the global balance of power. Fane's contributions during this period, though not as widely documented as those of his contemporaries, would have been crucial in the lead-up to one of the most significant conflicts of the 18th century.

## Personal Life and Legacy

Despite his prominent public career, Francis Fane remained unmarried throughout his life. His personal life, much like his political career, was marked by a sense of duty and service, though it lacked the personal connections that often define the narratives of historical figures. Upon his death on 28 May 1757, at the age of fifty-nine, Fane was buried at [Lewknor](/Lewknor) in Oxfordshire, a village that held significance for the Fane family.

Fane's death marked the end of a career that had spanned the legal, political, and administrative spheres of 18th-century Britain. His legacy, however, lived on through his younger brothers. His brother [Thomas Fane](/Thomas_Fane,_8th_Earl_of_Westmorland) inherited the Earldom of Westmorland in 1762, following the death of the 7th Earl. This elevation to the peerage was a significant achievement for the Fane family, cementing their place among the British nobility. Thomas's inheritance of the Brympton d'Evercy estate further solidified the family's ties to Somerset.

Fane's youngest brother, [Henry Fane of Wormsley](/Henry_Fane_of_Wormsley), also played a notable role in the family's history. The Wormsley estate, located in Oxfordshire, became another significant holding for the Fane family, and Henry's descendants would continue to shape the political and social landscape of Britain in the centuries that followed.

## Assessment and Historical Context

Francis Fane's career offers a fascinating lens through which to view the political and administrative machinery of 18th-century Britain. His roles as a Member of Parliament, a legal advisor to the Queen, and a commissioner for the Board of Trade and Plantations placed him at the intersection of law, governance, and colonial administration. His ability to navigate these spheres with competence and influence is a testament to his legal training and political acumen.

Fane's career also reflects the broader trends of the period. The 18th century was a time of significant expansion for the British Empire, with trade and colonial administration becoming increasingly central to the nation's economic and political strategies. Fane's work with the Board of Trade and Plantations situated him within this context, where he would have been involved in the policies that governed Britain's overseas territories. His legal background would have been particularly valuable in addressing the complex legal and administrative challenges that arose from Britain's colonial ambitions.

Moreover, Fane's parliamentary career coincided with a period of political transition. The fall of Walpole's government in 1742 marked the end of an era of Whig dominance, and the subsequent Pelham ministry faced the challenge of maintaining stability in a politically fractured landscape. Fane's ability to retain his seat and continue his service during these shifts underscores his adaptability and the respect he commanded among his contemporaries.

Despite his contributions, Fane's legacy has not been as widely celebrated as those of some of his contemporaries. This may be due, in part, to his lack of a personal narrative—his unmarried status and the absence of notable personal anecdotes have left historians with fewer avenues to explore his character beyond his professional achievements. However, his career remains a valuable case study in the workings of 18th-century British governance, offering insights into the legal, political, and administrative mechanisms that shaped the nation during this pivotal period.

